  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement preventive measures\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention Against Corruption\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Provides international banking standards for preventing money laundering\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establish regulatory requirements for financial institutions in EU countries\n\n5. International Monetary Fund (IMF) regulations\n- Provides guidance and support for combating financial crimes\n\nThese frameworks require countries to:\n- Criminalize money laundering\n- Implement reporting mechanisms\n- Establish customer identification procedures\n- Collaborate internationally on investigations\n- Impose penalties for non-compliance\n\nWhile these are international standards, actual enforcement happens at national levels through specific country laws and regulations.",
